<br>
Summon corpse in theory works same as locate corpse.<br>
<br>
Locate corpse picks the name of your target and feeds it into its filter, useing it with no target picks up neerest corpse.<br>
<br>
for isntance, a giant just died and fell into a loc, you miss clicked so cannot target and type /loot so you use locate corpse to target the giant, then /loot to grab its items.<br>
<br>
Same for players, have a friend at other end of zone targed the dead person, /assist friend so you get targed on the dead person, locate corpse... bam you just got a confirmed targed.<br>
Now imagine if summon corpse did not need you grouped, you could then just click on summon corpse and bam, you have there corpse when you are at other end of zone without ever meeting them.<br>
<br>
Summon corpse you need to be grouped with, the main reason is to avoid the thing above, you have one person at a mass grave, say clicking corpses, an necro at other end of zone /assist and summon a whole raid extreemly fast and with no hastle.. a bit to easy.<br>
So you make them group meaning that you both have to meet up and in higher lv dungeons it may mean zoneing out etc or fighting to the other group of players, wich takes time.<br>
<br>
Summon corpse does the same as locate, uses the players name to targed the corpse, then summon's the corpse... the spell is not a buff spell it only takes the name and uses it, heck the spell is not cast on the player really.. since it doesnt add a buff to the player, it only takes the name then casts the spell on the corpse, and a corpse is dead, it dont align much either way.<br>
<br>
SOOO to cut a long story short, if you didnt have to group you could summon any aligments corpse, but since we do.. you can only summon a corpse if you can group with them.<br>
<br>
This didnt cleer it up as nicely, but there you are, my words of wisdom. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
